"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810588","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-11","<p>We are currently consulting on the Supported Housing funding model. The Government is absolutely committed to protecting victims of domestic abuse. Funding for housing costs under the existing and proposed new models will continue at the same level. This funding will be ring-fenced and we intend this ring-fence to remain in the long term and local authorities will be required to do a needs assessment for all supported housing services, including domestic abuse.</p><p>We are also undertaking a root and branch review of how domestic abuse services are provided across England. The review will cover funding for refuges, and will be completed by Summer 2018. Thereafter, we will make decisions on the future arrangements for domestic abuse services. We are committed to working closely with the sector, drawing on their expertise and knowledge, so that we get this right.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-01-11T18:41:28.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810588/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810588/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-21","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of his Department's proposed new funding model for short-term supported housing services on the number of women and children who are turned away due to lack of provision.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","120933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810589","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-08","<p>The UK plan for tackling roadside nitrogen dioxide concentrations, published in July 2017, sets out the Government’s approach to improving air quality in the shortest possible time. The plan states that due to the highly localised nature of the problem, local knowledge will be crucial to solving pollution problems in these hotspots. We have put in place a £3,5 billion air quality plan, including £475 million specifically to help local authorities develop and implement their plans.</p><p> </p><p>There are a range of measures local authorities can introduce, such as retrofitting buses, changing road layouts or introducing Clean Air Zones should they consider this an appropriate solution. Local authorities already have the powers required to introduce Clean Air Zones under the Transport Act 2000. A framework published in May 2017 provides guidance on the approach local authorities should take to the introduction of Clean Air Zones.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-08T12:46:47.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810589/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810589/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-21","Clean Air Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will expand the national network of clean air zones.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","120934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810590","Department of Health","false","2018-01-08","<p>The McNeil Review into Public Health England’s (PHE) data collection and data management functions considered whether, how and when these should be transferred to NHS Digital. It identified four tranches of data, based on the complexity of the processes involved in the collection and quality assurance of the data and recommended that cancer registration be considered within tranche three and only after the earlier tranches had been completed; this is expected to take at least three years. PHE and NHS Digital are currently scoping the work programme to implement the review’s recommendations. PHE will continue to process cancer data in line with current legal gateways and the National Health Service rules on consent, taking into account any changes that may arise with emerging legislative and policy frameworks.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-01-08T16:44:38.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810590/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810590/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-21","Public Health England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for the implementation of the recommendations of the McNeil Review into cancer patient data at Public Health England (PHE), and what effect that implementation will have of PHE's adherence to NHS rules on consent.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","120935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810591","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-12","<p>Up to £55m of funding will be available to help support the programme making and special events sectors impacted by the 700MHz spectrum clearance programme. ​</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-12T15:30:52.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810591/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810591/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-21","Ofcom: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what funding her Department has allocated to Ofcom to promote in international forums the use of the (a) 961-1015 MHz, (b) 1045-1075 MHz, and (b) 1105-1154 MHz bandwidths for Programme Making and Special Events.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","120936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810592","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","true","2018-01-17","<p><del class="ministerial">Given current use in the 1350 – 1375 MHz band it is not considered feasible to allow sharing in this band for Programme Making and Special Events. The band 1375 – 1400 MHz is used by the Ministry of Defence.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">Ofcom have reported that within the band 1350 – 1375 MHz there are currently 817 links. The band 1375 – 1400 MHz is used by the Ministry of Defence.</ins></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-17T16:42:50.443Z","2018-01-18T10:12:34.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810592/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810592/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810592/answer/previousversion/34887","Biography information for Margot James","10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-21","Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many fixed links are operating in the spectrum between 1350 MHz and 1400 MHz.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","120937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810593","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-12","<p>Ofcom have reported that 2 manufacturers have stated their intention to have equipment that operates in the 960 MHz band on the market in the near future.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-12T15:28:54.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810593/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810593/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-21","Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans her department has for supporting manufacturers of Programme Making and Special Events equipment to build equipment for use in the (a) 961-1015 MHz, (b) 1045-1075 MHz, and  (c) 1105-1154 MHz bands.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","120938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810594","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-17","<p>Given current use in the 1350 – 1375 MHz band it is not considered feasible to allow sharing in this band for Programme Making and Special Events. The band 1375 – 1400 MHz is used by the Ministry of Defence.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-17T16:46:13.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810594/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810594/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-21","Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the feasibility of Programme Making and Special Events services operating in the 1350-1400 MHz band.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","120939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810595","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-12","<p>It is not possible to comment with any certainty on possible changes to spectrum use over a 10 year time frame.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","120941","2018-01-12T15:32:12.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810595/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/810595/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-21","Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what new services her Department plans on being introduced into the 1350-1400 MHz band over the next decade.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","120940"
